releases/0/tender/title: 16-074: Early Help Families for Change: Family Support Service
releases/0/tender/description:
Rotherham Borough Council is to commission family support provision to add capacity and align to the Early Help & Family Engagement Service in Rotherham. Early Help is about identifying needs within families early; and providing support before problems escalate, becoming more complex and costly. The vision for Rotherham's Early Help Services is that all agencies work together and share responsibility to ensure that children, young people and families have their needs identified early so that they can receive the swift offer of quality help and support. The provision to be commissioned will understand and meet the needs of vulnerable families in Rotherham as well as increasing the capacity of the in-house workforce. There is a commitment that every family will receive a holistic offer of support so that long term, sustainable change can be achieved, which will stop future re-referrals and duplication of work across the system. If you wish to be considered for this Tender you must register on the YORtender website and express an interest under YORtender reference ADSH-UACAC3, download the ITT documentation and complete and upload back onto the system by the deadline of 12 noon Monday 10th October 2016.

releases/0/tender/title: (APMS) GP Services for: Arboretum Surgery (Lot 1), Burton Road Surgery (Lot 2), Metheringham Surgery (Lot 3), Pottergate Surgery (Lot 4)
releases/0/tender/description:
NHS Arden and Greater East Midlands CSU (AGCSU) on behalf of NHS England Midlands & East (Central Midlands) and Lincolnshire West CCG is inviting suitably qualified and experienced providers to deliver the Service(s).

The current APMS (Alternative Provider Medical Services) contract includes the obligation to provide all Essential and Additional Services and a wide range of Enhanced Services within the requisite timescale to provide Alternative Provider Medical Services (APMS) for the below GP medical practices: 
•	LOT 1 Arboretum Surgery, 76 Monks Road, Lincoln, LN2 5HU, 
•	LOT 2 Burton Road Surgery, 181 Burton Road, Lincoln, LN1 3LT
•	LOT 3 Metheringham Surgery, High Street, Metheringham, LN4 3DZ
•	LOT 4 Pottergate Surgery, Vanessa Drive, Gainsborough, DN21 2UQ

This procurement will be conducted by AGCSU on behalf of Lincolnshire West CCG & NHS England, Midlands & East (Central Midlands) (referred to as the Commissioners).  

Any contract arising from this procurement will be between the successful Provider and NHS England (National Health Service Commissioning Board) and Lincolnshire West CCG as delegated commissioners on behalf of NHS England.  
The Commissioners are looking for a Provider(s) to deliver: 
a)	high quality, patient centred and value for money (VfM) Primary GP services delivered in a safe and effective manner
b)	Primary Medical Services including Essential, Additional and Enhanced services as set out in Document 3 – Service Specification. 
For this service provision Arden & GEM CSU would like to encourage innovative solutions including consortia, strategic alliances and sub-contracts which will deliver value for money and improved services to patients. 

Details of the individual practice profiles are attached to this notice and the ‘Attachments’ area on the Bravo portal. 

The Contract will be for a minimum period of 2 years with an option to extend for up to a further 12 months.  The contract for this service will be the NHS Standard APMS Contract, with an anticipated Service commencement date of March/April 2017. 

It is envisaged that TUPE will apply to this contract.

Based on the current contract it is anticipated that the service provision resultant of this procurement will have an annual agreement value as below:

1.	LOT 1 - Arboretum Surgery - circa £228,321 per annum (excluding V.A.T)
2.	LOT 2-Burton Road Surgery-circa £193,869 per annum (excluding V.A.T)
3.	LOT 3-Metheringham Surgery-circa £139,803 perannum (excluding V.A.T)
4.	LOT 4 - Pottergate Surgery - circa £306,387 per annum (excluding V.A.T)

All completed bids must be submitted by 12.00 Noon on 14 October 2016. The ITT reference for this tender is itt_548

All correspondence relating to this procurement throughout all the stages of the process must be managed through the Arden & GEM CSU eTendering Procurement Portal messaging facility only.

Additional information: All correspondence relating to this procurement throughout all the stages of the process must be managed through the Arden & GEM CSU eTendering Procurement Portal messaging facility only. 

The opportunity notices will be located on the following websites: 
https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search
http://ted.europa.eu/TED/main/HomePage.do



The services will be procured as per the Light Touch Regime detailed in Section 7 of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 (“The Regulations”), using the Open Procedure. It is worth noting here that NHS Arden and GEM CSU will only be bound by those parts of the Regulations that applies to contracts for Social and Other Specific Services.
The Health & Social Care Act 2012; in particular the regulations made under Section 75 will also be taken into consideration.

The Contracting Authority intends to use an e-Procurement Portal ‘Arden and Greater East Midlands CSU Procurement Portal’ in this procurement exercise. To access (please see web link below).: https://ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk/web/login.html

releases/0/tender/title: Heat Networks Delivery Unit Events and Communications
releases/0/tender/description:
The Heat Network Delivery Unit (HNDU), part  of Business Energy & Industry Strategy (BEIS), is looking for a contractor(s) to deliver a series of topical workshops,  conferences and training courses (collectively known as ‘events’ hereafter) for, but not limited to, local authorities, investors, consultants and BEIS internal staff as required on heat network development and delivery.  

These events need to be delivered regionally across locations in England and Wales and cover the full range of heat network topics, which includes both technical and commercial aspects of heat network development. Although we anticipate the need for sector specialists for specific events, we require the contractor(s) to evidence knowledge and experience of the heat network sector. This will enable the contractor(s) to organise relevant events as soon as the contract is awarded; have the ability to deliver generic heat network topic areas; be able to engage sufficiently with the market and tap into their own connections; and ensure messaging is in line with current policy whilst requiring minimal HNDU resource. 

The number of events will be demand led and based on HNDU’s requirements; however we anticipate roughly one event per month for the duration of the 24 Month contract. We will discuss events over the contract period, but the contractor(s) must be able to deliver events at short notice if an urgent need to communicate to the sector is required.

Additional information: How to Apply
If you wish to take part in this procurement please see the Tender documents attached to this Notice and send your completed Proposal to Marc Wormald at address stipulated in the “Who to Contact” section.
 Any late submissions will not be considered. BEIS reserves the right to halt the procurement process and to not award a contract. BEIS will not be held liable for recovery of costs from unsuccessful bids if a contract is not awarded. All costs will be borne by the bidding organisations. If a contract is created it will be upon BEIS Standard Terms and Conditions or the Short Form Terms and Conditions, which are available on Contracts Finder with this notice. Completed tender submission must be returned by post to BEIS, address given at the top of this advertisement, by 10:00 10 October 2016. We require 4 hard copies (one of which must be signed). Electronic versions of your bids are to be sent AFTER the deadline to Marc Wormald (hndu@decc.gsi.gov.uk). After reviewing and evaluating the written proposals, DECC may decide to hold bid clarification meetings with suppliers. If successful and upon contract signature, the supplier is expected to attend a kick-off meeting taking place week commencing 24 October 2016. This contract is for 24 months with the possibility of a one year extension. Number of events will be demand led and subject to continuing successful business planning outcomes securing budget.

releases/0/tender/title: Publication Service
releases/0/tender/description:
The University of Southampton is home to the Wessex Institute which oversees a growing number of research funding programmes, including those that are managed on behalf of the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) and Health & Care Research Wales.

The Wessex Institute provides high-quality, practice-based research to support decision makers in health and healthcare. We have particular expertise in added-value health research management and in health technology assessment, and host a growing number of nationally important, internationally recognised centres. Our other work includes scientific programme management and consultancy; we exist to make a difference to society through research.

The largest centre within the Wessex Institute is the NIHR Evaluation, Trials and Studies Coordinating Centre (NETSCC) which hosts the NIHR Journals Library, an internationally renowned open access journals series publishing a full account of research funded by the NIHR.  We are seeking a supplier of publishing production services to deliver the NIHR Journals Library taking full responsibility for all editorial and production processes from receipt of approved, peer-reviewed manuscripts to the delivery of digital files ready for publication in all standard formats.

NIHR Journals Library reports titles are well established and the contractor will be expected to provide files for online publication for the volumes that start in January 2018. The contract for producing the NIHR Journals Library will be between the contractor and the University of Southampton.  The contract will run for five years. 

Top level Evaluation Criteria at ITT stage Quality 70% / Commercial 30%

releases/0/tender/title: SS 15 98 - Volunteer Development Programme
releases/0/tender/description: Kent County Council (the Council) is the largest local authority in England covering an area of 3,500 square kilometres. It has an annual expenditure of over £1bn on goods and services and a population of 1.3m. The Council provides a wide range of personal and strategic services on behalf of its residents, operating in partnership with 12 district councils and 289 parish/town councils. This requirement is for utilisation by Libraries, Registration & Archives within the Growth Environment & Transport Directorate. The Council wishes to add value to the Council's Libraries Registration and Archives' services by managing and developing the role of volunteers to support Business Plan priorities. The Council has re-organised the LRA to commission its services against outcomes and so the specification has been developed to achieve this. The Council owns a softwarepackage,'Time2Give' which will be used by the Successful Contractor to support this programme. The Council would like to work with a dynamic, innovative and creative organisation that will be able to integrate Volunteers, by working with the Council through increased collaborative and proactive working practises that will continue to support the council's vision and strategic and supportive outcomes: The principal objectives of this opportunity are: To manage and develop the role of volunteers to support Libraries Registration and Archives. To include the work of operational front of house teams and Service Development Teams -Access Services, Business Support, Stock Services, Archives, Digital and Literary Services and Registration services.(The latter will include London Borough of Bexley Registration Services, provided under contract by Kent Libraries, Registration & Archives.) To embed and extend the current good practice. To ensure that all Library Registration and Archive volunteering is managed consistently, taking into account the individual needs of our services. To extend the range of volunteering activities and the services available in Libraries Registration and Archives and Kent's communities. To engage with local communities to develop and promote Libraries Registration and Archives' services. To provide training and development activities to improve staff skills and knowledge in the recruitment, retention, supervision and training of volunteers. To promote inclusion and diversity. To work within the Chartered Institute of Librarians and Information Professionals (CILIP) Guide lines for Volunteering to extend and add value to Libraries Registration and Archives' services.

Birmingham City Council invite organisations to receive tender documentation for the DEMOLITION AND ASSOCIATED WORKS INCLUDING SITE CLEARANCE OF 330 HOSPITAL STRRET, NEWTOWN, BIRMINGHAM B19 2NJ

Contract Number 12637

It is considered the two-storey former childrens’ centre of traditional construction is longer suitable for habitation and the site is earmarked for redevelopment, therefore identifies the need for safe demolition and site clearance. 
  
Contractors wishing to tender for this contract must have 3 years of audited accounts showing a minimum annual average turnover of £100,000.

The contractor must provide suitably trained workforce and experience/knowledge of works required to be undertaken. The contractor will be responsible for providing their own power, water and welfare to undertake this work.

A Public/Product liability insurance of £5 million and Employers Liability Insurance of £10 million must be provided.
The contractor must hold or employ persons with valid HSE asbestos license to be able to remove notifiable asbestos (if any).

The contract will be let using a Standard Form of Minor Works Contract 2011, with Birmingham City Council amendments.

It is anticipated the Contract period will be from 14 November 2016 to 20 January 2017. The successful contractor will need to demonstrate the ability to provide the service required, confirmation of conforming to demolition, asbestos and other relevant health and safety legislation, equalities and financial stability.

The estimated value of the works is in the region of £20,000.00 to £30,000.00.

o	online promotion and mail-out

o	tracking payment
o	submission and tracking reporting

•	Current grants/investments include:	
o	Partnership Investment
o	Development fund
o	Research and development
o	Arts Award
o	Managed
•	Events and Programme activity (internal and external tracking and reporting)
•	Booking function through website – using eventbrite and doodlepoll
•	Upload documents and images (pdf, jpeg, tif, csv, xls, doc, outlook files etc)
•	Import and run reports on all bridge data for national comparison (import and amend csv files)
•	Ability to add additional reports and tracking mechanisms when required
•	Ability to remove data upon request
•	Ability to save entire database as CSV file for export or use beyond the lifetime of the programme

This is a one off Procurement.

In order to understand the opportunities available in the marketplace, Great Baddow Parish Council (The Council) invites potential suppliers to express an interest and to discuss outline proposals to provide the maintenance of the Recreation Ground and Noakes Park, Allotment sites and other ancillary sites in Great Baddow.

The Council manages two allotment sites in Great Baddow, which will include maintaining grass pathways, strimming unused allotments and cutting hedges.

The standard of work must be at a premium level on both sites and in carrying out such work, the Contractor and his staff will exhibit a caring attitude, showing respect to mourners and staff employed by funeral directors and memorial masons, and others visiting the cemeteries.
Spraying will be required and a suitably qualified person will be needed to carry out this work.
The length of any contract is not yet decided but initial indications are that it will be for 3 years.

To arrange an appointment to discuss this further please contact:
Ann Wood, Clerk of the Council, 19 Maldon Road, Great Baddow, Chelmsford, CM2 7DW on info@greatbaddowparishcouncil.co.uk

releases/0/tender/description:
This Framework  Contract will be available for use by the Council and any;

•	public or private entity (including limited companies) in which the Council has a shareholding or interest;

•	maintained school (as defined in the Academies Act 2010) within the Borough of Gateshead which have entered into a buyback agreement with the Council which provides for the supply of goods or services of the type to which this Contract relates or which enter into such an agreement at any point during the term of this Contract;

•	Academy schools (as defined in the Academies Act 2010) which have entered into a buyback agreement with the Council which provides for the supply of goods or services of the type to which this Contract relates or which enter into such an agreement at any point during the term of this Contract.
This Framework contract is being let by The Borough Council of Gateshead. 
Gateshead Council is seeking to enter into a Framework contract with numerous/multiple suppliers who can efficiently provide a range of Construction Small Plant & Tools in specific kits for 13 different trades/disciplines which will assist the Council in delivering a high quality cost effective Housing Repairs and Maintenance Service together with other operational Construction Services.
The Council has recently approved the intention of directly delivering the Housing Repairs and Maintenance Works and Services.
The Framework will be divided into Lots as detailed within the specification and outlined below :-
LOT 1 – TRADE KIT Consists of a number of different kits for 13 specific trades/disciplines containing a range of power tools and equipment relevant to specific trades. The tools must be provided in kit form and packaged in a suitable holdalls/carry cases where appropriate for easy portable transit. Lot 1 will be awarded to ONE supplier. 
Kit 1 – Bricklayer
Kit 2 - Electrician
Kit 3 – Floor Layer
Kit 4 – Glazier
Kit 5 – Joiner
Kit 6- Labourer
Kit 7 – Semi-Skilled Operative
Kit 8 - Painter
Kit 9 - Plasterer
Kit 10- Plumber
Kit 11 – Gas Plumber
Kit 12 – Gas Engineer Service & Repair
Kit 13 – Roofer
It is estimated that approximately 179 kits in total for Lot 1 will be required.
An estimated breakdown of each trades’/disciplines’ kit content requirements is detailed within specification for pricing purposes.
LOT 2 – GENERAL TOOLS AND EQUIPMENT Consists of a range of more general tools and equipment which will supplement the trade kits outlined in Lot 1. Lot 2 will be awarded to ONE supplier.
It is estimated that approximately 179 kits in total for Lot 2 will be required.
An estimated breakdown of each trades’/disciplines’ kit content requirements is detailed within specification for pricing purposes.
SUPPLIERS CAN BID FOR ONE OR BOTH LOTS.

releases/0/tender/description:
Appointment of a bona fide certified brokerage insurance agent to source and procure a underwriters policy, the latter which will provide a medical health support plan to the Medical Research Council (MRC) personnel and families located overseas. The MRC's research Units are primarily in The Gambia, West Africa and Uganda, East Africa for "ex-pats" work and require the provision of a company comprehensive health support plan (renewable yearly) for accessing local and UK medical facilities for themselves as MRC workers and their families. The appointed broker will be expected to provide to the MRC management and it's staff a full claims management and claims administrative service from first episode to settling of claim(s) cycle. 

Supplementary to the sourcing of the medical health plan a Africa to UK travel cover policy will needed via the appointed broker.

Additional information: DO NOT CONTACT THE BUYER TO APPLY FOR THIS PROCUREMENT, PLEASE FOLLOW BELOW INSTRUCTIONS.

As part of the strategic alliance between UK Shared Business Services Ltd (UK SBS) and Crown Commercial Service (CCS), UK SBS can use the CCS eSourcing Suite for future procurements.

If you have not yet registered on the eSourcing Suite, this can be done online at https://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk by following the link ‘Register for CCS eSourcing’. Please note that, to register, you must have a valid DUNS number (as provided by Dun and Bradstreet) for the organisation which you are registering, who will be entering into a contract if invited to do so.

Once you have registered on the eSourcing Suite, a registered user can express an interest for a specific procurement. This is done by emailing Expressionofinterest@crowncommercial.gov.uk.

Your email must clearly state: the name and reference for the procurement you wish to register for; the name of the registered Bidder; and the name and contact details for the registered individual sending the email. Crown Commercial Service will process the email and then enable the Bidder to access the procurement online via the e-Sourcing Suite. The registered user will receive a notification email to alert them once this has been done.

The Sourcing documents can then be accessed on the eSourcing Suite at: https://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk using the instructions detailed in the Specification documents within Contracts Finder. 

As a user of the e-Sourcing Suite you will have access to Emptoris email messaging service which facilitates all messages sent to you and from you in relation to any specific RFX event. Please note it is your responsibility to access these emails on a regular basis to ensure you have sight of all relevant information.

For technical assistance on use of the e-Sourcing Suite please contact Crown Commercial Service Helpdesk : Telephone: 0345 010 3503 Training documents to support Bidders utilise Emptoris CCS eSourcing are available in the Contracts Finder Tender documents section.

releases/0/tender/title: Customer Experience in the Water Sector - Future Customer Performance Commitment and Service Incentive Mechanism (SIM) Review
releases/0/tender/description:
The overall objective of the work is to identify and evaluate alternative approaches to measure, evaluate and compare company performance in terms of customer service, satisfaction, trust and confidence.

Scope and key tasks

The Contractor will be expected to:

1. Identify/confirm the main challenges of the current SIM as a measure of company performance in terms of customer service, customer satisfaction and customer complaints.	
2. Assess complementarity of current SIM against existing common Performance Commitments (potentially informed by our initial quantitative analysis).	
3. Identify the outcomes which could be measured (eg. customer service, satisfaction, trust, confidence), set out the interactions between these, and identify options for measurement.
4. Identify/confirm evaluation factors.
5. Assess options for measurement against the evaluation criteria, and produce a shortlist of recommended measures.
6. Consider the possible governance / funding models for the options.

We welcome views on different or additional steps we would need to consider to ensure we meet our objective.

Key Outputs and Deliverables

Interim outputs
•	We expect to see interim outputs associated with the different key tasks set out in part 3 above. 
•	Subject to project set-up discussions, this can be eg. in PowerPoint format and be part of the ongoing project management and progress update meetings.

Draft Report
•	At the end of the research the Contractor will be required to produce a draft report for the Customer by an agreed date. The Contractor should factor in sufficient resource to meet the production of multiple iterations of the draft report if necessary.
•	The Customer will comment on the draft reports by agreed dates.

Final Report
•	The Contractor will then be required to produce a final full report for the Customer which will address the Customer’s feedback on the draft report. The report will need to include overall conclusions and recommendations. 
•	The Contractor should provide, as an appendix to the final report, all relevant supporting evidence underpinning the report’s main conclusions. This needs to include relevant interview notes, bibliography etc.

Findings slide package
•	The Contractor will also be required to present the report’s key findings in a PowerPoint/infographics format, for use by Ofwat as needed.

releases/0/tender/title: Call-Off Econometric Modelling Services - Cost Assessment
releases/0/tender/description:
Objectives

The Customer seeks expert advice on the econometric modelling of water companies’ costs for the purposes of setting price limits at the 2019 periodic review.

The Contractor must be able to provide robust advice that can withstand scrutiny from the water industry and other stakeholders.

The Contractor will be required to:

•	Provide general advice and consultancy services on matters relating to efficiency and cost assessment.
•	Inform Ofwat’s decision making on econometric modelling, reviewing, refining and updating a set of models.
•	Provide expert advice on Ofwat’s approach to econometric modelling of water company costs and activities. 
•	Undertake advanced econometric modelling to assess cost efficiency.
•	Provide documentation for the work undertaken.
•	Comment on cost assessment and efficiency analysis carried out by the companies themselves, other stakeholders and by other contractors.

Scope and Key Tasks

Ofwat will provide data to the Contractor for their scrutiny, opinion and advice on the use of econometric modelling tools. The Contractor will be required to use econometric methods to analyse data provided by Ofwat:

•	To assist in reviewing, refining, updating and developing a set of models to determine efficient costs for the water and sewerage companies;

•	To provide general advice and consultancy services on matters relating to efficiency and cost assessment, including written documentation.

Deliverables and timeframe

Ofwat will start receiving new data for cost assessment from the water companies in August 2016. We aim to consult on our approach to cost assessment in one or two stages starting from June 2017.

Ofwat will provide guidance on the timing of the key deliverables which will align with the price review timetable and any subsequent price review referrals. These will include (but are not limited to):

•	advice on econometric modelling of cost functions;

•	development of appropriate models and advice on integrating these models into Ofwat’s wider approach to cost assessment;

•	contributing to Ofwat policy papers and discussions on cost assessment; and

•	contributing to industry working groups on cost assessment.

Additional information: Please note that this is a call-off contract so it is difficult to quantify  exact spend.

releases/0/tender/title: Student Accomodation Project (Mount Oswald)
releases/0/tender/description:
Durham University (the ‘University’) has developed a new University Strategy (2017-2027) that envisages growth in the number of students who will require College accommodation. Overall, it is anticipated that there will be growth of approximately 6 000 students, mostly undergraduates. This number will include c. 1 700 students who are being relocated from the Queen's Campus in Stockton-on-Tees, as the University seeks to consolidate its education and research activities onto the Durham City campus.
 As part of a supporting strategy of estate development, the University has identified a need for additional student residential accommodation. To deliver part of this additional need the University has acquired the Mount Oswald site with the benefit of outline planning consent for 1 000 bedspaces. As a Collegiate University, colleges form a major part of the delivery of the Wider Student Experience, and therefore the University is looking to deliver the new accommodation at Mount Oswald through the design and construction of two new colleges, each of approximately 500 self-catered student bedrooms, plus associated college infrastructure and common space.
 This procurement brings to the market the opportunity to take forward the delivery of the two new colleges and the associated accommodation on the basis of a design, build, finance and operate model.
 The Mount Oswald site is well located close to other colleges, the Durham University Business School (DUBS) and the main University campus. The new accommodation will include a mixture of en-suite and shared bathroom bedrooms arranged in cluster flats and town houses to meet the varying needs of the college students, including first year and returning under-graduate and post-graduate students. An important element will be the provision of social and study space, together with college administration facilities.
 The University's preference is for the delivery of both
 colleges as early as possible, with at least 700
 bedrooms, plus all the associated social and
 college administration facilities being available for
 occupation by the commencement of the 2019/20
 academic year, any balance to take the bedroom
 numbers up to the total of 1 000 to be available by the commencement of the 2020/21 academic year.
 The duration of the contract is to be up to a potential maximum of 50 years (from practical completion of the colleges). Ongoing operation of the colleges will include the successful bidder delivering hard FM services and some or all of the soft FM services, with the University delivering any balance. The exact allocation of soft FM Services will be determined during the dialogue phase of the procurement.
 To express an interest please follow link:

releases/0/tender/title: Wheelchair Services
releases/0/tender/description:
Herts Valleys CCG and East and North Hertfordshire CCG wish to engage with providers with expertise and experience to deliver the following wheelchair services for residents within Hertfordshire who have long-term mobility problems: 

               • Clinical assessment and prescription, review and re-assessment 

               • Purchase and provision of equipment, modification and adaptation of equipment to meet individual needs

               • Repair and maintenance including planned preventative maintenance, delivery, collection and training, refurbishment.

Market Engagement Event: 14th October 2016

Providers in the market place will have the opportunity to meet and talk to Herts Valleys CCG and East and North Hertfordshire CCG staff and patient representatives involved in the commissioning of this service.  It is expected that the market event will be an interactive session, providing an overview of the existing service and current prevalence, and will seek ideas, suggestions and comments as to what the new service could provide and how it could be delivered. 

This event is intended only to gather information from the market, and to request information which may be relevant to the development of any eventual procurement strategy/tender. For the avoidance of doubt this notice is NOT a call for competition.

The scope and structure of these services may be further developed following this market and stakeholder engagement and currently anticipated requirements may change as a result of this ongoing activity. 

If you would like to attend the Market Engagement Event registration can be made from the following link: http://events.constantcontact.com/register/event?llr=lvlgvjfab&oeidk=a07ed6lc92v3e8c4dec

Additional information: As set out above, this notice is intended only to inform the market of a prospective contract opportunity and to request information which may be relevant to the development of any eventual procurement strategy/tender. 

In the event that Herts Valleys CCG and East and North Hertfordshire CCG decide to formally commence the procurement it is anticipated that a contract notice will be submitted via the OJEU in November 2016.
 
Suppliers who wish to ask questions in relation to the services without registering to attend the Market Engagement Event can send email requests to: CPHenquiries@eoecph.nhs.uk   Any resulting procurement will be managed electronically, details on accessing documentation, and the e-procurement portal address will be provided in due course. 

Potential providers will not be prejudiced by any response to this event or PIN published in the OJEU, or failure to respond. All information made available to those attending this event will be made available to bidders who express an interest in any resulting procurement. 

This PIN does not formally signify the beginning of a procurement and does not constitute a commitment by Herts Valleys CCG and East and North Hertfordshire CCG to undertake any procurement exercise. 

In the event that Herts Valleys CCG and East and North Hertfordshire CCG decide to formally commence the procurement for the supply of services a separate contract notice will be issued in the OJEU and Contracts Finder.
